Are key influencers regularly speaking for themselves in the public communications?
Is all or most communication explicitly published by an executive level change leader?
Can participants see alignment of their preferences and responsibilities as influencers?
Can participants easily see where their own impact is benefiting progress?
Do management leads show collaboration with each other in discussions and decisions?
Are proposed impacts described both as outcomes and support?
Does messaging consistently treat change effort as being driven by stakeholders’ benefits?
Are existing legacy communication channels directing staff to the shared change tracking?
Are work managers successfully translating the right ideas into the right languages?
Is a “best place to work” story coming through clearly in communications?
Do employees have simple always-on access to a dashboard & scorecard of change initiatives?
Is knowledge development clearly identified as both a requirement and an opportunity?
Can staff see and promptly recognize plan modifications that change their own expected contribution?
Can staff contribute easily to the business process designs?
Is a performance management system used to support talent and skill development for change?
Does each distinctive contributor (individual or workgroup) have a profile of their role capability that is easily discoverable  company-wide?
Do terms of cooperative agreement usually frame requests and discussions  for collaboration?
Are stakeholders routinely acknowledged for their performance and impact as collaborators?
Are program managers usually part of the change design team?
Is impact analysis of proposals done before approvals occur?
Are all participants invited to join the impact assessment?
Are projects sized for deliverability instead of for other reasons?
Is production defined by deliverables more than by process?
Do new proposals usually incorporate the output of other current or proposed changes?
Are both legacy and new methods being adapted to prioritize change execution (not just business-as-usual) effects?
Does recommended practice accept a range of methods for meeting  objectives?
Do workers have sufficient autonomy to create solution proposals for any change?
Can functional workgroups confidently take on a full time posture as service providers?
Do all “collaborators” accept equal accountability in agreeing to share work?
Is leadership recognized independently of job titles?
Are all workgroup members able to see when they should initiate adjustments among the workgroup?
Does performance evaluation of processing recognize a range of outcomes as being valuable?
Is the individual’s employment security increased with commitments to change initiatives?
Is always-on user and technical support explicitly established to help FTEs manage change?
